VALUES ('c9cfd69e-2e27-4455-b022-f3b57080514d', 'Which finding, if true, would most directly support Dr. Morales''s hypothesis?', 'Urban sociologist Dr. Morales hypothesized that community gardens logging at least $15$ weekly volunteer hours produce larger harvests than gardens with lighter volunteer turnout, but only when cultivation methods are held constant across sites. In gardens where managers changed fertilizer regimes mid-season, Morales predicted volunteer hours alone would not reliably predict harvest size. She tracked 3 gardens through one growing season, recording weekly labor and total vegetable yield in pounds. The authors caution that replication remains necessary before treating the finding as settled.', 'passage', '[{"id":"A","text":"Among gardens with fixed cultivation methods, sites averaging at least $15$ volunteer hours per week harvested $811$ pounds, whereas sites averaging fewer than $10$ hours harvested $411$ pounds.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Compares high- and low-hour gardens under fixed cultivation, directly testing the labor threshold claim."},{"id":"B","text":"Every garden in the study harvested more than $361$ pounds regardless of volunteer hours or fertilizer changes, yet the comparison omits the pairing required to test the passage claim directly, a figure.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Unconditional Support Decoy] Harvest floors without hour comparisons do not test the hypothesis."},{"id":"C","text":"Gardens that switched fertilizer regimes mid-season showed higher soil nitrogen readings than gardens with fixed regimes, independent of volunteer hours, a figure accurate in isolation but not linked to the.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Irrelevant Variable] Soil nitrogen under fertilizer changes is outside the volunteer-hour prediction."},{"id":"D","text":"Among gardens with fixed cultivation methods, low-hour sites outproduced high-hour sites by $141$ pounds on average, describing one row only rather than the cross-row contrast the claim requires., which restates table.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Inverse Support] Low-hour gardens outproducing high-hour sites contradicts the predicted labor effect."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Step 1 — State the claim
Focus on {{yellow:methods}} in the passage. The textual evidence item asks you to state the claim before comparing choices.

Step 2 — Find supporting language
