VALUES ('a309f183-e016-496e-8491-f8f763ca1a48', 'Which finding, if true, would most directly support Dr. Sato''s hypothesis?', 'Marine biologist Dr. Kenji Sato hypothesized that invasive lionfish predation significantly reduces native teleost fish populations on coral reefs, but only in reefs characterized by low structural complexity. In reefs with high structural complexity—defined by dense, branching coral architectures—Sato predicted that lionfish predation would have no statistically significant impact on native fish populations, because complex physical structures provide ample refugia for prey species. His team monitored paired reef plots for 20 months, standardizing water temperature and excluding unrelated fishing pressure so habitat structure remained the primary variable under study.', 'passage', '[{"id":"A","text":"In both highly complex and simple reefs, native teleost populations decreased by approximately $27\\%$ within six months of the introduction of invasive lionfish species, but the statement fails to contrast the groups named in the.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Unconditional Support Decoy] Shows decline in both reef types, ignoring the required buffering effect of structural complexity."},{"id":"B","text":"Reefs with high structural complexity saw an increase in macroalgae cover of $13\\%$ after lionfish were introduced, while reefs with low structural complexity experienced a decline in water clarity, accurate yet non-diagnostic because it.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Irrelevant Variable] Addresses macroalgae and water clarity rather than native teleost populations."},{"id":"C","text":"In reefs with low structural complexity, native teleost populations remained stable after lionfish introduction, while lionfish populations themselves declined due to increased predation by larger reef sharks, reporting a ranking without the harvest or.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Inverse Support] Stability in low-complexity reefs contradi